Connected Conversation: Tea & Talk with HeatherAsh
A Warrior Goddess community-building hour of connection and love-filled learning.

Join me for 60 minutes of improvisational topic weaving, new-friend making, and a brief respite.

What is improvisational topic weaving, you ask?

It’s where I take three topics (that you get to vote on right after you register below and weave them together for a rich and illuminating live lesson with the purpose of bringing joy, curiosity, and connection to everyone in attendance. Topics include things like: letting go, boundaries, confidence, pleasure, healing, rage, etc...

Our time together is designed to connect you with new and old friends and meet me directly so you get a brand new opportunity to plant some seeds of community that we all so desperately crave in these complicated times.

And I promise, we will keep things light and heartfelt (my specialty). There will be fun prizes, laughter, and piles and piles of love. You’ll get to ask questions and learn new things, but most of all, you’ll get to spend an hour away from whatever feels heavy and hard for you right now.

Come exactly as you are: pajamas or ball gown, with joy or with grief, feeling stuck or feeling free.

All genders, expressions, and current life experiences unconditionally welcomed.

Join me (and so many others!) and bring your favorite mug of whatever soothes you. There will be prizes for the best one. Save your seat HERE: ➡️ LINK IN BIO!

This time of year is all about the bright sunshiny idea that if you just make a resolution to lose weight or exercise or be a better person and you stick to it you’ll become a better, slimmer, calmer, more enlightened version of yourself by February.

F**k that, dear ones.

You don’t need to fix or judge or resolute yourself into being the perfect, youthful, always happy version of yourself that the media and marketing mavens claim will make you happy.

You don’t need another list to beat yourself up with, or a goal that disconnects you from where you are right now and leaves you grasping for what you think you should be or want.

This year’s Anti-Resolution Challenge runs Wednesday, January 11th - Tuesday, January 17th and includes guidance to UNDO the ways you might be tied up by old fears in fight, freeze, flee, or fawn mode and GET UNSTUCK from unconscious strategies of controlling, pleasing, isolating, or distracting. 

Instead of making another DAMN LIST to do, let’s root out the unhelpful stories and patterns we’ve learned so we NATURALLY regain our creativity, inspiration, and magical mojo.

Hey loves,

Today is not just a day to just quote Martin Luther King Jr. and then not think about his legacy or work until next year; today is a day to be in service, to educate ourselves about racism, to lean in to discomfort. 

Step one: Go read more about MLK Jr if you don’t know his full story. From Wikipedia: “His adoption of nonviolent resistance to achieve equal rights for Black Americans earned him the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964. King is remembered for his masterful oratorical skills, most memorably in his "I Have a Dream" speech."

If you want support for this important work; whether you are brand new to antiracist work or have been learning for decades (for the learning never stops) know that we have created two forms of support: Bi-monthly gatherings for BIPOC run by Warrior Goddess mentor Sarina Harz (learn more by emailing sarina@warriorgoddess.com) and a bookclub (and 6-month course that starts again in March) for white women.

I'll be hosting the next book club on The Quaking of America on January 26th. It is a very intense book; don’t feel you have to read all of it, but I highly recommend reading through the intro and some exercises. Also, you might want to read his first book, My Grandmother’s Hands, first.

Feel free to join me for simple somatic work, discussion, and readings from The Quaking of America.

Last night I finished the last section of my new book. I took a break, danced around, cried a bit. Then I started re-reading everything.

And I hated the writing.

When I woke up yesterday, high on almost completing the book, it was the favorite book I've written to date; by bed I was ready to give up being a writer.

It felt all wrong, jumbled, and unfinished. This is a terrible book, I thought. I'm going to have to start over. It is a total mess.

This morning I woke and remembered: right, this is the lovely part of the writing journey where I hate ever thing and want to hide comfortably under a bed for the rest of my days.

The first draft is done but the book still needs editing and paring down and sprucing up. I want it to be DONE. It still has a ways to go. 

I cannot believe my mind right now AT ALL. Because I'm feeling vulnerable, and spent. I just ran a writing marathon, and I need some distance to recover. Then I will be ready for the next marathon of editing and strengthening the words.

KEEP PADDLING!
DON'T JUMP OUT OF THE BOAT!
THE ONLY WAY OUT IS THROUGH!

It is actually our judge that is deciding what is “healed” rather than listening with our open-hearted support to the brilliant weaving of thoughts, energy, emotions, and body that we are.

When we stop abandoning ourselves and learn how to separate out the fearful and punishing thoughts we discover what support we actually need to heal our whole selves.

Many of us think of alchemy as the secret process for turning different metals into gold. That is one form of alchemy, but there are many, many different types of alchemy.

Today is exactly one year since the wildfire went through our land outside of Santa Fe National Forest, New Mexico.

And today is the launch of something really important to me: my new substack, Out of the Fire: Dancing with the Contradictions.

I've been working on this new outlet for my writing since January, and I'm feeling tender, vulnerable, and relieved to be finally sharing it.

❤️ 

Out of the Fire, born from a literal wildfire, is dedicated to having the hard conversations surrounding the most critical topics of our time.

And Out of the Fire is also about opening to the beauty, the bravery, and the brilliance phoenixing all around us.

What do we do when the world seems to be burning around us?

We hold hands. We show up. We take good action and make good trouble. We root in. We pray. We love. We weep. We sing to the trees. We know we are in this, together.

My intent with Out of the Fire is to dance together with the contradictions, and find meaning in the chaos. And to celebrate everything.

For now I’ll be sharing writings every other week, and plan to start a podcast in Fall 2023.

As a writer it helps my brain to take a step back regularly and look at what I have written and what my deadlines, dreams, and focus is for articles in the future. It is fairly easy for me to write one article a week for my email newsletter; and now that I'm wanting to start writing on Substack weekly as well I need to be more thoughtful and systematic. 

Email newsletters take me about three writing sessions; so far my Substack articles take me about 10 - 15 writing sessions because they are much more in depth and challenging (I'm writing about dancing with the contradictions, after all, which takes some tango waltz tai chi moves).

By having a list of all the articles I'm planning to write in the next two months I can work on different ones as I feel inspired, and am also super clear about what my deadlines are. And I'm adding in podcasts as well to see if I can stay on a schedule with them, too. Experimentation!

When you have two hours to finish editing your book and your goddaughter comes over to you, book in hand, and says, “HeatherAsh, will you play with me?”

Walking up to the sacred stones of Calanais on Isle of Lewis a couple of days ago, something shifted inside of me. I was returning home to my maternal ancestors, walking on the actual land where they walked and loved, lived and died. My mother’s ancestry is 100% from the British Isles. Mine is 95%.

Like my mother, I also have a high percentage of Neanderthal in my blood (apparently 94% higher more than most people). And so it was such an affirmation when I learned that the Calanais standing stone circle, which was built 2,000 years before Stonehenge, was built by Neanderthals.

My people, until the 1800’s, loved their land fiercely and did not leave. They may have traveled, but they married and farmed and raised their children in a very small portion of the world. 
 
As I walked into the circle of the 13 ancient gneiss stones that were placed 5,000 years ago I felt a sense of awe and connection. This land is my indigenous home. This tiny island at the most furthest western edge of the European continent holds the bones and sweat and love of my ancestors.
 
I’ve sought and found connection in so many places around the earth; and I will continue to travel and explore and learn from other cultures, other ancestral traditions, other rocks and waters and plants. And yet. There is a place that my body actually knows intimately, soul and cells and threads of DNA reaching back through time.

This is the land where my 5th great-grandmother, Anne MacLeod, died in 1800. In 1820 Anne's daughter Jessie MacKenzie and her husband Donald Ross "took the lease of a quarter share of the farm of Gisla, giving this up shortly after 1825, and emigrating to Nova Scotia." (from ancestry.com)

I stood on that land and poured an offering to the earth, whispered my thanks to the spirits of that place and to the to the resiliency of my family. I imagined what it was like to have to leave this land. Jessie and Donald had eight children before they left Isle of Lewis. This was a time called the Highland Clearances:

"...the forced eviction of inhabitants of the Highlands and western islands of Scotland, beginning in the mid-to-late 18th century and continuing intermittently into the mid-19th century. The removals cleared the land of people primarily to allow for the introduction of sheep pastoralism. The Highland Clearances resulted in the destruction of the traditional clan society and began a pattern of rural depopulation and emigration from Scotland."

As I wrote in my last newsletter, not all of us have the gift of knowing where are ancestors are from. But truly, it is not necessary. I already had an intimate and supported relationship with my dead ancestors long before I traveled to Outer Hebrides. In earth-based shamanic traditions there is no time and space, no place we cannot travel in our inner journeys. 

Our ancestors (both blood and beloved) are always nearby, willing to share their wisdom and support.

- People who were total assholes while alive might become your best allies when dead. Truly.

Imagine a huge willow tree, rooted solidly into the earth. Whether skies are clear or there is a torrential downpour, whether there is a sweet gentle breeze or wild winds, the willow bends but does not break. 

The tree does not curse at the weather or try to avoid the wind. It roots in deeper, and gets more steady for the next storm.

And what is also crucial is understanding that stillness and steadiness is an inside job that we can learn to access despite the noise and wobble outside of us.

Today, on my day off, I’ve been watching videos of dead Palestinian children, of kidnapped Israeli women, of children buried under the rubble of war, of families dispossessed. 

I’m trying to understand.

I don’t understand.

And I totally understand.

Today, I don’t turn away. I want to see, to take it in.

So I breathe, and watch. 

Oh, humans. We are so, so cruel to each other.

Why when harm is done do we think more harm is the answer?

Why do we try to erase the history of oppression, and then are shocked when violence spills over?

Why do hurt people create more hurt? 

How do we stop the cycle?

I remind myself: wars and atrocities and hurt are happening everyday, everywhere around the world.

What we are seeing in Israel and Palestine (or Ukraine and Russia or in Iran, or Afghanistan or…) is not an isolated case or a sudden outbreak of violence or repression, but a long-time simmering that has boiled again to the surface. Just like in so many places around the world. 

There are currently 23 ongoing armed conflicts happening on our little planet earth.

How do we metabolize the news, the images, the hatred, the murder, the grief?

Sharing some raw thoughts with you. A sentiment that kept replaying in my mind over the weekend is the idea of “heartbreak making way for fertile ground.” This extremely difficult time that we’re processing through as a global community has left our hearts tender… and while we’re advocating for justice & calling for ceasefires, many of us are sitting in that brokenness. Yet that tender space can also be a place where new seeds of change can be planted. Not just hoping for it, but taking steps to reorient ourselves to what’s good & right & true by dedicating ourselves to new rhythms while we try to get through our days and all our current responsibilities.

You may have discovered that you haven’t been as in-tune with global news as you want to be (I know I’m not), yet now is a chance to plant that seed and tend to it by looking for unbiased outlets and seeing how you can create a new rhythm of being informed without being completely overwhelmed. Or you’re finding how important language is and how easily entire people groups can be dehumanized. You can plant this seed and tend to it by choosing to define your terms, remember context, & sprout that habit of avoiding harmful rhetoric as you discuss tough topics.

If you’re looking for something tangible as you make your way through this week, swipe for a blank chart that you can fill with 1-3 new rhythms to try dedicating yourself to. I doesn't start out that way. At the beginning of this apprenticeship retreat at Warrior Heart Ranch last week there were at times hesitation, resistance, fear, rough edges bumping. But within a safe container and supported by the teachings everyone started to trust and open.

Honoring my papa, Gerard Robert Gaudet, over Samhain / Dia de los Muertos.

When I was young my dad saved me from a monkey who had grabbed my hair and was pulling me towards its cage; jumped in to save me from drowning when I had the bright idea to put my arm floaties around my ankles; and probably a thousand other ways he kept me from harm.

He was steady, patient, and kind. He loved to travel and explore. He was raised Catholic but became a Buddhist when we lived in Thailand.

We had many battles over the years, mostly around politics and perfectionism. For years I didn't feel like he really saw who I was.

Then one day in Peru, on a teaching journey my mom and dad had joined me on, my papa said something that made me realize that he really, really did see who I was. It rearranged my internal world.

I was with him when he crossed, talking to him and holding his hand. Even though he was unconscious for the last few days, he knew I was there. 

He held me as a child, and I held him as he crossed. Circles upon circles of love.

I'm so grateful to continue to have a relationship with my dad on the other side. And with all my other beloved death.

Tonight our group in Teotihuacan will build altars to the dead, and open up the pathways of communication between the worlds. We will continue healing our ancestral lines, and honoring those who have crossed. I'm so grateful to be here for Day of the Dead, celebrating the ancestors with so many others in Mexico.

Loves, here is the new cover of my upcoming book, Wild, Willing, and Wise: When to Paddle, When to Rest, and When to Jump Naked into the River of Life. 🥰

I'm doing the final final final edits this week in cafes throughout Cusco, which is so fun!

It has been such a journey to birth this baby, which is my 9th book. 

My last book with St. Martin's Press, Warrior Heart Practice, came out in January 2020. I still believe it is the best book I've written, yet because of the pandemic I wasn't able to truly tour and share it fully. 

Wild, Willing, and Wise actually started out as a completely different book: a memoir about a really difficult time of my life. But as I was working on the memoir throughout 2021 and the world was in such chaos and challenge, my coach Illana asked me: do you really want to be writing this particular book right now? What do you need, and what does the world need from you?

I sat with that question for a long time. Any my answer was: something digestible, practical, with a bit of humor and easy to follow steps for skillfully navigating stormy waters and learning to rest into calm flow.

So I put the memoir aside and started a whole new book.

The seed of the book came from my curiosity about the three archetypes of the Maiden, Mother, and Crone. But then as I wrote it deepened into something so much more. (Sarina, who has read all of my books multiple times, swears it is her favorite book of mine. I hope you will love it as much as Sarina does! It is pretty damn fun and fierce.)

Now this is the hard part....  we all have to wait for the book to be birthed into the world!  On July 30th, 2024 Wild, Willing, and Wise will be released. My team and I are planning a huge book release and tour both live and online; anyplace you'd like me to come do a book talk or workshop? Let us know!

OH and next year is also the 10th year anniversary of Warrior Goddess Training, and my publisher @hierophantpublishing is going to be printing a special anniversary edition : )

Perdita, Sophie, and I prayed together for our mutual friend Matthew while he was in surgery, while we also laughed at the antics of Sophie’s dog Baba Ganoush and drank coffee strong enough to raise the dead. We called on ancestors to guide the hand of the surgeon and hold Matthew with tenderness. We linked our hearts and our voices as we prayed together. Later we lit a special candle at the shrine.

I just looked at a post Matthew sent me from November 2015 ( last pic) It was a special day: Matthew and I took a bus to Woodstock to meet Perdita and Clark for the first time. Matthew had read Clark's book, Waking up to the Dark. Inspired, we started praying the rosary together, and eventually he was inspired to create a Kali rosary practice that I still use today. They live in Woodstock. WE HAVE TO MEET THEM! I said.

Perdita and Clark agreed to meet us for lunch, and we took the bus. I still remember the feeling of the bus pulling up, seeing Perdita and Clark waiting for us, and the feeling of hugging them for the first time. Since 2015 our lives have woven together so beautifully and tightly. Clark and Perdita wrote the stunning book Way of the Rose. Their incredible daughter, Sophie, published her masterpiece The Madonna Secret. Perdita has a new book that I love and highly recommend, Take Back the Magic. 

Yesterday as Perdita and I chatted over tea, she gave the me the critical piece for a memoir I'm working on. YEEEEEE! I'll spend January in Woodstock writing it, taking long walks, and drinking tea on the couch with Perdita.
